<subSubSection pageId="181" pageNumber="182" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="181.[189,457,401,427]" box="[189,457,401,427]" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,457,401,427]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="181" pageNumber="182" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,457,401,427]" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">Differential diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="181.[189,1399,447,579]" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin, 2018" authorityName="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2018" box="[329,734,447,473]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="181" pageNumber="182" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dentata" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis box="[329,734,447,473]" italics="true" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">Sphegina (Asiosphegina) dentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[749,848,447,473]" pageId="181" pageNumber="182" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Brunetti" authorityYear="1915" box="[920,1154,447,475]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="181" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tricoloripes" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis box="[920,935,449,475]" italics="true" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[957,985,447,473]" italics="true" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">(A</emphasis>
.
<emphasis box="[992,1154,447,473]" italics="true" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">) tricoloripes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. For distinguishing characters, see under the latter. In the male genitalia the species is reminiscent of a few other 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Stackelberg" authorityYear="1974" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="181" pageNumber="182" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">Sphegina (Asiosphegina)</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which have the cerci as large or larger than the surstyli. It differs from all these by the unusually large and humpbacked tergum IX.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="181" pageNumber="182" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="181.[189,324,618,644]" box="[189,324,618,644]" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,618,644]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="181" pageNumber="182" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,618,644]" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="181.[189,1399,665,726]" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin ‘ 
<emphasis box="[749,862,665,691]" italics="true" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">umbrosus</emphasis>
’, meaning ‘dark-shaded’ and referring to the overall dark brown colour of the body and especially the dark-shaded legs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
